titleStmt.title: Cambridge, Cambridge University Library, MS Add.1138

respStmt.resp: Edited by Michael Marx in collaboration with Tobias J. Jocham et. al. TEI version created by Yasmin Faghihi and Huw Jones

summary.p: 96 folios; Writing surface: parchment; Shelfmark: MS Add.1138; Qurʾānic text: Q 23:1-95, Q 23:99-118, Q 24:1-19, Q 24:21-31, Q 24:31-64, Q 25:1-20; 5 Lines per page; Dimensions: 125 x 80mm; Script style: kūfī D.Va; Estimated date of production: 3rd century AH / 9th century CE.

Fragments of an Abbasid Qurʼān (probably third century A.H. / ninth century C.E.), containing verses from the Sura al-Muʾminūn (سورة المؤمنون), the complete Sura al-Nūr (سورة النور), and verses from the Sura al-Furqān (سورة الفرقان). The script seems to correspond to the Abbasid Style D.Va as described by F. Deroche. For more information about the manuscript, see the entry in the Digital Library of Cambridge University.

The University of Cambridge acquired the fragment in 1878 from Edward H. Palmer (1840-1882) and E.E. Tyrwhitt Drake. The displayed fragment and other early Qur'an manuscripts (call numbers Add. 1115 - Add. 1150) were acquired by Palmer during a research trip to the Sinai Peninsula (cf. Ansorge 2016).
